for the same ingredient.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:45.839
Awesome. Well, let's, we'll jump in here. I get to ask some of the questions in the beginning

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:52.399
while we wait for questions to come in from everybody. But at the Hangouts, we do often

00:04:52.399 --> 00:05:00.959
talk a bit about hiring, but it's more often from the employer side, but thinking more from the

00:05:00.959 --> 00:05:07.200
candidate side. I know somebody had reached out to me about that last week too. I know you both

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:13.679
have some experience transitioning from academia to industry, and would love to just learn a little

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:19.600
bit from you about maybe some tips you might have for us or people who are in a similar position.

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:21.440
Joe, I'll let you go first.

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:32.320
Okay. Yeah, I'm selecting on my own path. And then I also still speak with a lot of people

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:38.880
regularly who are transitioning. And I'll try to offer the advice that I wish I had, you know,

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:43.600
six years ago, which is that like, if you're coming out of an academic background, it's easy

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:50.000
to feel like you're not qualified or you're unprepared for tech careers in industry.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:55.600
And that's really, really far from the truth. You're actually, you have an incredibly unique

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:01.839
and valued skill set. The challenge is learning how to talk about it in ways that a non-academic

00:06:01.839 --> 00:06:08.399
is going to recognize. And I hope that's something you get out of today. And so, and this doesn't

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:12.880
just apply to academics. You know, if you had a career previously in like nonprofit work or

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:15.760
government work, and you know, you're thinking about transitioning to tech, I think a lot of

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:21.200
this is going to apply for you too. And so, what are the big things? Like, I think it would be easy

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:28.000
to miss your soft skills. And I don't use that soft term dismissively at all. They are the most

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.119
valuable skills. And these are things like the ability to take a vaguely scoped problem and turn

00:06:33.119 --> 00:06:39.359
it into an actionable line of research. If you finish the PhD, you know how to do that. Other

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:44.559
factors like your ability to translate your expertise to people who are intelligent, but

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:51.119
don't share your particular expertise. That is a huge skill set. You know, in order for you to

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:56.160
have influence within your organization, you're going to need to translate your expertise to

00:06:56.160 --> 00:07:01.279
leaders and other stakeholders who, you know, don't have your particular background. And you've

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:08.079
got a lot of practice in public presentation and translation during your academic experience that

00:07:08.079 --> 00:07:14.079
most people never get. I was never formally trained in public presentation until I got into

00:07:14.079 --> 00:07:20.000
my PhD program. And then, just out of like self-preservation, you know, your lab members

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.880
to protect the, you know, reputation and integrity of the lab, they're going to give you a lot of

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:31.359
guided feedback on how to present well. So, it's easy to get hung up on like, oh, I don't know how

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:36.880
to do this particular modeling technique in Python. And it's like, those are the hard skills

00:07:36.959 --> 00:07:42.559
in the sense of like soft skills, but you can learn those pretty quick. You're bringing in a lot

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:47.679
of soft skills that are very, very rare. They're so rare, they're not going to be in the job posting

00:07:47.679 --> 00:07:53.920
a lot of times. You're going to need to proactively plug them throughout your resume, throughout the

00:07:53.920 --> 00:08:00.880
interview process. And I promise you, you will see the hiring managers perk up when they start

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:05.839
hearing about these really rare abilities that you've had the last five, six years to develop.

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:13.200
Yeah. And I guess to add on to that, I think there are two things that kind of come to mind for me

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:19.760
here is that one is that expertise is truly relative, right? Anybody who works in industry

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:26.720
knows this. You easily are the expert on XYZ thing in your organization because as long as you

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.799
provide, as long as you know more about that than anybody else in your organization,

00:08:30.799 --> 00:08:35.520
you are the resident expert. And I think that when I was transitioning, that was one thing that

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:40.000
I worried about is, oh, I don't know enough. But I was just talking to somebody yesterday and I was

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.640
telling her like, you already know way more about this industry than anybody I've ever hired.

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:49.599
And 10 out of 10 times, I would rather take somebody who knows a little bit less about the

00:08:49.599 --> 00:08:54.799
industry, but has a proven track record of being able to learn very quickly and can pick it up.

00:08:54.799 --> 00:08:59.119
Right. So I think that's something that anybody who's in this room is clearly interested in

00:08:59.119 --> 00:09:03.919
learning and is curious and wants to improve their skills. So I have no doubt about that.

00:09:03.919 --> 00:09:10.000
That's kind of the first thing, like expertise is relative. And then the second one is kind of,

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:14.000
you know, what Joe was saying is you're trying to translate your skills into something that

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.559
your audience and people who are hiring can understand. One of the best pieces of advice I

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:24.320
got was from David Kelly, who kind of established the design thinking method and the d.school at

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:30.159
Stanford. And he really talked about how, you know, every industry and every organization

00:09:30.159 --> 00:09:36.000
is really just a group of people who get together and kind of decide what the standards are. Right.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.320
And you all know this in data science, the standards and data science have been evolving

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:44.960
and shifting and what's really high quality and the cutting edge has changed a lot.

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:50.159
And so in order to actually understand how to translate your skills into what's most valuable,

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:55.200
I personally think one of the only ways that you can do it is you have to talk to people

00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:01.840
and you have to talk to a lot of people to understand how they what like even the specific

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:06.559
words that they use to describe certain skills can be sort of signals to them that, you know,

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:12.320
or understand how things will work. And so I remember going to David Kelly and saying like,

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:18.960
oh, I'm debating between these two jobs right now. One is like position A and the other one is

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:24.080
position B. Do you think if I take position B, it'll make it hard for me to do position A stuff

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:30.320
later on? And he was like, Jen, like I'm not an expert in this field, but it's knowable.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:34.640
And if you don't understand the answer yet, it's because you haven't talked to enough people in

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:39.599
the field. You need to talk to enough people to like wrap your arms around the norms of that

00:10:39.599 --> 00:10:45.280
group and then you'll know the answer. So I think the takeaway there for me is like you need to talk

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:50.559
to people to understand what they value and how the community works, but also that it's knowable.

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:54.559
I think a lot of people assume that you can't get that kind of understanding until you've been

00:10:54.559 --> 00:10:59.359
working in that industry for multiple years. And certainly your understanding will, you know,

00:10:59.359 --> 00:11:04.559
you'll get a lot more once you work in it. But if you talk to a lot of people, you can get like

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:07.679
80, 90 percent of the way there for a job decision, I think.

00:11:08.559 --> 00:11:12.559
I want to jump on top of that one because really it's really good about talking to people.

00:11:12.799 --> 00:11:21.599
LinkedIn is an incredible tool for making the transition. And maybe I don't know a lot of

00:11:21.599 --> 00:11:26.479
people in industry yet. I didn't know. I didn't either at one point. And actually, you'll find

00:11:26.479 --> 00:11:34.000
that cold calling on LinkedIn can be very, very effective. I typically look for people who had

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:39.039
like a PhD in their name or who I could see had some academic background or some background

00:11:39.039 --> 00:11:44.799
similar to mine, and then just reach out and say like, look, I'm trying to make the transition.

00:11:44.799 --> 00:11:48.799
Could you spare 15 minutes to talk to me? These can be very vulnerable conversations.

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:51.280
You're not trying to impress them right now. You're trying, like Jen was saying,

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:55.840
to get like a lay of the land and to scope like how your skills might fit in.

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:02.479
And overwhelmingly, those people actually turn into your backers. Like they'll submit your

00:12:02.479 --> 00:12:07.760
resume internally, really just after an hour meeting. Like they'll see that you're like a

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:14.640
thoughtful, resourceful person. And you're a safe bet. But to Jen's point, like you learn the lay

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:20.239
of the land so that you're better prepared to talk about your skills and what you have to offer.

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:26.559
And also to know for where you'd fit in. Absolutely. I see Sita, you had a question

00:12:26.559 --> 00:12:32.880
in the chat a bit earlier. Do you want to jump in? Sure. My camera always acts. Oh, there we go.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:40.799
Hey. So I was really intrigued by the conversation about transitioning from academia to industry.

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:46.880
And I would really like to understand because hopefully that's a direction I would want to

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:52.960
pursue because I am a pure biologist trying to transition into data science. And I work at the

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:58.479
data science lab now at the Hutch. And I'm really trying to understand where I go from knowing all

00:12:58.479 --> 00:13:04.960
this intense biology knowledge, which is purely bench skills and now moving into more genomics

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:12.960
and technology driven and using these newer technologies to really understand and answer

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:20.559
genomics questions. But for me, what has been interesting in this even medium shift from being

00:13:20.559 --> 00:13:25.359
in the lab to being in a data science lab where people are focusing on building more reproducible

00:13:25.359 --> 00:13:30.960
workflows, et cetera. One thing that I feel like there's a stop gap is when I was a postdoc, I was

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:36.479
like leading my project. I was in charge. I was determining the scope and the future of that

00:13:36.479 --> 00:13:42.640
project. And here I'm just a part of something which is also really exciting. But then you feel

00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:48.880
like a sense of less control in a way and more directed. And I kind of wanted to see what you

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:58.159
guys thought of that. Thanks. My experience has been that like the job levels within data science

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:04.799
are very tied to how much direction versus self-direction you're going to engage in. So

00:14:05.599 --> 00:14:11.760
when you come in as like a base level data scientist or analyst, your work is very highly

00:14:11.760 --> 00:14:19.359
scoped for you. It tends to be like execute this solution to oversimplify it. You move up a level

00:14:19.359 --> 00:14:25.119
and now you're being asked, you know, find a solution to this problem that I'm giving you.

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:30.719
You move up another level to staff and now you're being asked choose which problems are worth

00:14:30.719 --> 00:14:37.119
solving. And so like as you move up your scope and the amount of autonomy and responsibility

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:43.359
you have for directing your work, it keeps increasing. But so yeah, I would say like,

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:46.880
you know, your experiences, yeah, as you get started, your work tends to be more scoped.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:52.000
But then as you demonstrate that you can choose good solutions and choose problems worth solving,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:57.119
you tend to be given more and more autonomy. And then, you know, the responsibility and promotions

00:14:57.119 --> 00:15:03.760
go with that. Yeah, I think the other thing that kind of your question, by the way, I'm loving

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:09.440
this chat. There's so much like good sharing from everybody. But one of the other things that I was

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:14.799
thinking about, too, is that essentially, right, with any job and any organization, there are

00:15:14.799 --> 00:15:19.760
tradeoffs. And so I think one of the big tradeoffs with academia, in theory, at least, is that

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:24.080
with academia, you're supposed to get like full intellectual freedom, although hard to get until

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:28.719
you get tenure. But, you know, in theory, you get full academic freedom and you can kind of pursue

00:15:28.719 --> 00:15:36.080
and set a lot of your own schedule and your work. And the reason I think you can do that is that

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:42.000
your lab or where you work kind of, they act autonomously, right? They're in their own line

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.479
of research, etc. When you go into a company, especially the bigger the company gets,

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:51.599
there are just more interdependencies, right? You're trying to work on things that affect and

00:15:51.599 --> 00:15:56.320
interact with more people. But the tradeoff for that is that oftentimes the impact and the reach

00:15:56.400 --> 00:16:01.760
is also very different, right? So in academia, you're kind of in your little area. You want to

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:06.719
make an impact. Oftentimes, people do it by building a body of work after many, many decades.

00:16:07.679 --> 00:16:13.039
In industry, you kind of get that tradeoff where, I mean, the example I think of is I worked at

00:16:13.039 --> 00:16:18.400
ThredUp, where, you know, we're a medium, by the time I left, we were like a medium-sized company,

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:23.039
we were public. I have friends who worked at Meta, where when they send an email to their

00:16:23.039 --> 00:16:29.280
customer base, it goes out to 50 million people, right? And so like their scope is actually large,

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:34.000
but their interdependencies are also incredible and the amount of cross-functional work they

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.440
have to do is very, very high compared to what I had to do. So I think you just get that tradeoff

00:16:39.440 --> 00:16:44.960
depending on where you go. And is that kind of a challenge when it comes to even hiring

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:52.559
pure academics, where they kind of have that, is that one of the challenges when hiring people

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:58.320
who are more traditionally academic and transitioning into this? Or do you find that

00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:02.239
people often quickly transition and that's not really something you're thinking of

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:08.079
when hiring people from traditionally academic backgrounds?

00:17:09.599 --> 00:17:15.520
I think this goes into that translation piece. I can think of three hiring examples where we

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:21.920
took someone right out of academia and they started at a staff level. That's two

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:28.319
levels up from an entry-level position in data science. And we did that because they demonstrated

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:33.760
their ability to scope and direct their work based on their academic experience.

00:17:34.719 --> 00:17:39.520
Like those are those soft skills that I was saying, they're really hard to find. But if you can

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:45.199
translate that soft skill into terms that your hiring manager can understand,

00:17:45.199 --> 00:17:51.359
you can come in at a very high level. If you don't come in at such a high level,

00:17:51.359 --> 00:17:55.280
I think nonetheless, you would rapidly rise to that level. Because as I said, it's a rare skill

00:17:55.280 --> 00:18:01.599
set. And so if you demonstrate it, you will be given the additional autonomy and responsibility

00:18:02.239 --> 00:18:11.680
because we need people to do that kind of work. Thank you both. Thank you. I see, Jared, you

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:17.520
had asked a question a little bit earlier about different educational backgrounds for data science.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:23.599
Do you want to jump in? Hi, Rachel, can you guys hear me okay? Yep. Yeah, so I guess my question is

00:18:23.599 --> 00:18:29.680
just more of a blanket statement. But given just from these data science hangouts in general, people

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:36.239
come from such a wide variety of backgrounds when it comes to data scientist positions. Have you guys

00:18:37.040 --> 00:18:43.680
found that there are certain educational backgrounds or, I mean, not just technical

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:48.239
skills, we've talked about soft skills, but really just focused on educational backgrounds

00:18:48.239 --> 00:18:55.520
that help seem to put people in a better position or seem to be more common than others

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:04.719
and kind of demonstrate a road for success? If you're ready. Rachel, maybe actually I'll jump in

00:19:04.719 --> 00:19:11.920
your answer. Yeah. Yeah. So the word self-reliance comes to mind.

00:19:14.079 --> 00:19:20.000
Incredibly diverse background among the people I work with. And oftentimes they learn their initial

