of my favorite stories, one of the guys I work with, he was an online gambler and got really

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:35.760
sophisticated about it. And, you know, you could see how that would play into like predictive

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:43.040
modeling and the data science workflow. And I tend to really see a lot of that where it's just,

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:48.560
you know, they're very like self-driven and self-engaged with their education. And,

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:53.680
you know, I'm not sure how many on the call today are academics. I'm seeing in the chatter that

00:19:53.680 --> 00:19:59.920
there's a lot, but, you know, you know that a big part of the PhD is self-education. You know,

00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:06.479
the coursework is not like really the emphasis. You have to teach yourself a lot of skills around

00:20:07.119 --> 00:20:10.719
programming or figure out how to get the resources you need to learn those new skills. And

00:20:11.839 --> 00:20:15.760
so that's the background I see because you're going to continuously be learning on the job.

00:20:16.719 --> 00:20:20.880
And so if you can demonstrate that you have a history of doing that, I think that's what sets

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:26.560
you up for success. Are those like that mindset that, you know, you can find the resources you

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:36.959
need to learn the next thing. Yeah. I think also, I think one thing that's kind of challenging

00:20:36.959 --> 00:20:42.239
about data science as a field, I think, and I would say the same coming from product is that

00:20:42.239 --> 00:20:48.239
it's a more, it's a newer field, right? It's a little bit younger than like software engineering

00:20:48.239 --> 00:20:54.160
or some other fields where that those fields have been a little bit more defined for longer.

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:58.800
There are programs you can get an undergrad in engineering. They're like clear leveling paths,

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:01.920
you know, in these tech companies that have been established for a long time.

00:21:02.479 --> 00:21:09.040
Data science is a little bit relative to some of these other areas is still evolving quite quickly.

00:21:09.040 --> 00:21:14.160
The technology is changing very fast. The methods are changing, you know, even our approach to like

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:17.920
AB testing, I feel like over the last five years has gotten, has gone through like multiple

00:21:17.920 --> 00:21:22.800
revolutions. And so I think that is one of the challenges for people coming into it is figuring

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:28.959
out, okay, well, how do I position myself? What do I spend time like investing skills in? And I think

00:21:28.959 --> 00:21:34.079
to this point, I think I agree with Joe. I think the ability to learn new things and figure out

00:21:34.959 --> 00:21:39.280
like where to learn and grow next is really important. Kind of our earlier point about

00:21:39.280 --> 00:21:43.439
talking to people and actually figuring out what's on the cutting edge of the field and what might be

00:21:43.439 --> 00:21:48.959
worth worth it and what might not be is really important. And then I think like for academics,

00:21:48.959 --> 00:21:55.119
this is actually not dissimilar, I think, to your PhD research is that oftentimes those fields are

00:21:55.119 --> 00:21:59.920
changing. If the methods are changing, you want to figure out the best method to answer the question

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:04.800
that you're looking for and you may need to learn new things. So, so I do want to call out, like,

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:09.680
I do think that's something, there's not a very standard, standard path that like, if you just do

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:15.439
these things, things will be guaranteed. And that can make it very tricky. It also means that,

00:22:15.439 --> 00:22:19.920
you know, kind of what Joe was saying, your technical skills are not enough. You have to

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:26.239
have this combination of technical skills and the ability to sort of navigate organizations and talk

00:22:26.239 --> 00:22:30.479
to people and build relationships, because I think it's the combination of those two things that

00:22:30.479 --> 00:22:37.040
makes people, that actually helps them. There's, yeah, there's a piece there that ties a few themes

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:40.959
together, which is like, we mentioned like informational interviewing earlier. So, you know,

00:22:40.959 --> 00:22:44.719
you learn how to talk about yourself, you learn about where you're interested. You're also going

00:22:44.719 --> 00:22:53.680
to learn what data science means at that company. It's not a standardized definition. And I'll say,

00:22:53.680 --> 00:22:59.680
I have generally found there are two verticals. There's like a machine learning AI vertical,

00:23:00.319 --> 00:23:04.800
that tends to be about like automating decision making. And if you're automating small decisions,

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:09.760
like what should I put in my cart next? What should I watch next? And then there's an analytics

00:23:09.760 --> 00:23:17.040
vertical. And that tends to be very thoughtfully constructing big decisions, like which market

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:24.400
should we pursue next? You know, which product feature should we launch next? And those are

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:29.199
very different. And, you know, you may find that you're more qualified for one or the other. If you

00:23:29.199 --> 00:23:33.199
have a ton of machine learning and predictive analytics experience, like maybe going down that

00:23:33.199 --> 00:23:38.640
ML path is going to be really promising for you. If you're really into like theory building and

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:44.079
like understanding customer behavior, that analytics vertical can be a fantastic fit.

00:23:45.119 --> 00:23:48.560
Because they're not going to call it theory building, but like, what are you doing? Like

00:23:48.560 --> 00:23:52.079
you're developing customer narratives, you're trying to understand customer behavior.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:56.079
And then you're trying to change that behavior in, you know, hopefully positive ways.

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:02.239
And that is very close to the theory building that you did as an academic, they're just,

00:24:02.239 --> 00:24:05.680
again, translating, they're not going to call it theory in industry, they're going to call it like

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:11.760
narrative and context. And so I saw a great comment about can I count my years of PhD and

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:17.520
postdoc experience as industry experience? Absolutely. If you can convince the hiring

00:24:17.520 --> 00:24:25.280
manager that those years were relevant experience, then they count. And in my mind, they count. And

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:30.800
you should be very confident in claiming that they count. I love in the beginning, we were talking

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:36.640
about like everybody's first jobs, and we were commenting in the chat. But also, in hangouts

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:41.359
before, we've talked about all the different kinds of paths that people take to get to the

00:24:41.359 --> 00:24:48.239
roles that they're in now. And I know, not everybody is going to have a PhD, of course,

00:24:48.239 --> 00:24:56.959
to go into data science. But I was wondering if you have other guidance for people in that

00:24:56.959 --> 00:25:02.719
position when maybe the job posting is calling for that? How do you get past that?

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:09.439
Well, maybe I'll start. I think one thing I do want to kind of set the tone on is that

00:25:10.079 --> 00:25:16.880
there is, in my ideal world, when it comes to hiring, how you would do things is that

00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:22.479
you actually think about the job that you need to hire for, you step back, and you really think

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:28.880
about what competencies we're really trying to hire for. And then you try to find candidates who

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:35.040
have the ability or the potential to meet those competencies. And those competencies are whatever

00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:41.199
skills we're looking for and are somewhat unrelated to, I saw a note about a Stanford PhD,

00:25:41.199 --> 00:25:46.800
are unrelated to the school you went to, whether or not you have a PhD. It's very unclear to me if

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:51.520
the PhD is the most efficient way to get any of these skills. So even though both Joe and I have

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:55.599
it, we could have a different conversation about whether or not the PhD is the right thing to do.

00:26:00.160 --> 00:26:05.839
So I think that's kind of the ideal world. And actually, a lot of the research on good hiring

00:26:05.839 --> 00:26:09.920
practices supports this general model, where you actually want to think about the competencies,

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:14.160
and you actually want to hire for people who have those competencies, no matter how they got them.

00:26:14.880 --> 00:26:19.520
Now, the reality of the world is a little bit different than that, which is that

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:24.239
hiring managers are often using proxies to try to get at those things, right? They'll use the degree

00:26:24.239 --> 00:26:28.880
as a proxy, they might use the school that you went to as a proxy. And so I just kind of want to

00:26:28.880 --> 00:26:35.280
say that out loud as like the first kind of the context, which is the world is not at the ideal

00:26:35.280 --> 00:26:40.400
stage, I think that many of us would want to be. And so we have to both like, I was once told,

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:45.599
you know, you want to move the world towards the world that you want it to be, but also recognize

00:26:45.599 --> 00:26:50.719
the realities and like, address the realities right on. So I think when there are certain

00:26:50.719 --> 00:26:56.160
requirements that are on there, hard requirements, I think you do have to do a little bit more work,

00:26:56.160 --> 00:27:01.520
basically, to try to convince somebody. But I do think that that work is possible. And again,

00:27:01.520 --> 00:27:06.000
it kind of goes back to, I think, some of the same themes, which is like, if you have a soft

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:10.800
intro to the hiring manager, you've talked to somebody internally, that's a much easier case,

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:16.719
I think, to kind of get your name in the game and actually get that conversation and show that

00:27:16.719 --> 00:27:23.199
you have those competencies. I think another way is, I've seen some incredible resumes where they

00:27:23.199 --> 00:27:30.239
didn't have sort of the requirements that maybe were listed. But they had a way of basically

00:27:30.959 --> 00:27:34.959
articulating the skills that we were looking for, or even in the way that they constructed,

00:27:34.959 --> 00:27:38.560
the resume showed us that they would be able to communicate these things very well.

00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:42.160
So there are things like that. But I think in today's like hiring environment, which is a

00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:46.719
little tighter than it was, you know, a couple of years ago, like one of the biggest things I would

00:27:46.719 --> 00:27:51.359
say is like, if you can find a way to get yourself in front of the recruiter or the hiring manager,

00:27:51.359 --> 00:27:56.400
like getting in that door is probably one of the hardest steps, I think, in today's hiring

00:27:56.400 --> 00:28:02.079
environment. But Joe. So Rachel's initial question was like, you know, if you don't

00:28:02.079 --> 00:28:06.640
have the PhD background, like, you know, how can you prepare yourself for this track? And

00:28:07.199 --> 00:28:08.640
yeah, I think like Jen and I were alluding, like,

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:15.040
getting a PhD is not the efficient way to gain these skills. It just happens to be the way that

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:21.040
we took. I can tell you my counterpart in the other hand, the other side of the company has no

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:25.359
PhD, we have the same title, like, you know, and his 401k is probably in way better shape.

00:28:27.199 --> 00:28:34.560
So you don't need a PhD. It's just that, you know, I wanted to say like, if you have one,

00:28:35.439 --> 00:28:39.760
like, there are some skills you inefficiently gained along the way that now you can capitalize

00:28:39.760 --> 00:28:44.800
on. But if you're not going that route, um, I said I heard some wonderful advice from someone

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:50.079
I was speaking to a posit conference, they applied at Apple. And the hiring manager told

00:28:50.079 --> 00:28:53.040
them gave some great feedback. They're like, you're not ready yet. But here's my advice.

00:28:54.239 --> 00:29:01.280
Get a job as an analyst at a small insurance company. And the idea was that then have access

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:08.239
to some like great, highly relevant data. And the idea was just like, while you're in that small

00:29:08.239 --> 00:29:17.040
shop, just like knock their socks off. You know, like, use all of the great like open source free

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:24.000
resources that are available in R and Python, and just like build yourself an amazing portfolio.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:29.040
And I think this was amazing advice, because actually getting a hold of relevant data with

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:36.479
signal in it is hard. It's not available at every company, but like, an insurance company probably

00:29:36.479 --> 00:29:40.800
does have it, you know, there's like the right incentives to get that kind of data in place.

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:45.199
So I think, you know, if you put yourself in that kind of environment, where you have access to that

00:29:45.199 --> 00:29:51.599
data, and then you use it to build up your skills and demonstrate your skills, like, you know, at

00:29:51.599 --> 00:29:54.319
the end of the day, like when you're high, when you're when you're interviewing, you're only going

00:29:54.319 --> 00:30:00.479
to get to tell like, two or three stories. You know, I mean, like, it's, it's actually quite

00:30:00.479 --> 00:30:04.640
limited how much of yourself you're going to get to show. So like, you know, you think about like,

00:30:04.640 --> 00:30:09.040
okay, you know, you, you have a resume with some bullet points of like things you've accomplished,

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:14.079
and you have two or three persuasive stories. If you're really ambitious, like I would recommend

00:30:14.079 --> 00:30:20.000
starting a blog so that you can like, you know, do more publication, not publication in the formal

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:25.520
sense, but just publicizing of, you know, your ability to communicate and to make compelling

00:30:26.160 --> 00:30:32.640
narrative and compelling data viz. But that would be very ambitious. I rarely see that

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:39.040
even among people we hire a blog would be like, you know, very impressive, but but just again,

00:30:39.040 --> 00:30:45.199
you know, find a position where you have access to some interesting data and, and then kind of

00:30:45.199 --> 00:30:48.479
just kind of keep building your skills incrementally from there and demonstrating it.

00:30:49.199 --> 00:30:54.000
Yeah, you don't need the PhD to do this kind of work. It's more of that self starter,

00:30:54.000 --> 00:31:00.560
self reliance that PhD really requires. So it becomes like a signal of that ability,

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:05.439
but it's not the only way. It's like we say, it's a very inefficient way. It takes five or six years.

00:31:06.400 --> 00:31:10.959
So I see, Mike, you have your hand raised. You want to jump in here?

00:31:12.400 --> 00:31:16.719
Thanks for that. It actually wants to come back to something that Jen just said,

00:31:16.719 --> 00:31:24.959
which I think is really important. It's almost like the CV screening process is done by people

00:31:24.959 --> 00:31:31.199
who don't actually, you know, they're, they're, they're using something to just to go in, out,

00:31:31.199 --> 00:31:38.079
in, out, rather than, you know, a holistic look at what actually that person can do. You know,

00:31:38.079 --> 00:31:44.479
and so it's like that, that kind of screening filtering happens way before anyone who has a

00:31:44.479 --> 00:31:50.400
data science background might even look at your CV. Sorry, I may be putting words in your mouth,

00:31:50.400 --> 00:31:56.479
Jen, but you know, it seems to me that any, those kinds of things are completely arbitrary and

00:31:56.479 --> 00:32:00.719
completely unfair because they happen so far removed from the hiring manager sometimes,

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:06.719
that I'm wondering how we redress that. I think, well, I think between Joe and I,

00:32:06.719 --> 00:32:11.839
we have experiences with like a wide range of companies, right? So Joe has worked for startups

00:32:11.839 --> 00:32:16.239
all the way to big companies. And so I guess like I would say kind of two things here. One is,

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:21.520
so I'll give two examples of my job search, which wasn't, I was actually looking at data science

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:26.880
jobs when I first entered the market. So a couple of things, one, and I'll, I'm going to give my

00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:33.920
example, but it's an extreme example. So just like, so I kind of knew in December, I defended

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:39.439
my dissertation in May. I knew in December that I wanted to go into industry. So I just used that

00:32:39.439 --> 00:32:43.839
time to informational interview. And I had these hypotheses and I just talked to a lot of people.

00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:50.160
I talked to a lot of people. I ended up because I had never done a job in tech. I had no idea what

00:32:50.160 --> 00:32:54.079
a recruiter was. I was like, why am I talking? Who is a recruiter? Like, what do they do?

