I never do it. And for the simple reason that even with the great credential,

00:35:40.159 --> 00:35:49.600
I would routinely get desk rejected. It requires networking, like cold calls on LinkedIn,

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:54.080
finding people who are second and third degree contacts and asking for introductions.

00:35:54.080 --> 00:36:01.120
Now, I will admit that for many people, even for me, that is painful and unwanted activity.

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:07.120
But you can flip that around and think of it as your advantage that most people aren't willing

00:36:07.120 --> 00:36:16.080
to engage in that kind of knocking on doors, essentially, cold calling to network their way

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:22.399
in. Now, once you get that referral, now you have a much higher likelihood of actually getting the

00:36:22.399 --> 00:36:31.120
initial part of the interview started. But that kind of networking doesn't end at the interview

00:36:31.120 --> 00:36:36.639
process. That's a big part of the job, too. I mean, once you're internal, so you know,

00:36:36.639 --> 00:36:41.919
congratulations, you've now been hired and you're doing work. Well, you're still going to need to

00:36:41.919 --> 00:36:48.639
figure out how to network within your company in order for your projects to get greenlit,

00:36:48.639 --> 00:36:53.840
for your projects to go into production. That is a skill unto itself, too. And so if I see

00:36:54.639 --> 00:37:01.520
candidates who are doing that networking in order to get that internal referral, that's a good

00:37:01.520 --> 00:37:05.199
signal to me that they're going to be willing to do the kind of personal networking when they're

00:37:05.199 --> 00:37:11.439
inside the company as well. Submitting to the portal and hoping for the best is just such

00:37:11.439 --> 00:37:17.199
low likelihood. And once you're inside, finishing your project and pushing to GitHub and hoping for

00:37:17.199 --> 00:37:22.399
the best, that's not going to be enough. You're going to need to figure out whose buy-in do you

00:37:22.959 --> 00:37:28.159
need, get their feedback in advance. It's like they're completely parallel processes,

00:37:28.159 --> 00:37:31.439
getting into the company and then performing once you're inside the company.

