00:39:43.760 --> 00:39:50.639
careers are not made by one job, right? So just because in that one job you're optimizing maybe

00:39:50.639 --> 00:39:59.199
say for comp and geography doesn't mean that your entire career will not be focused on culture,

00:39:59.199 --> 00:40:05.199
mission, and things like that. And I think thinking of your career and your jobs as

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:11.040
steps along the way that's building like a larger career portfolio has been really useful for me. So

00:40:12.399 --> 00:40:16.159
I think you need to think about what are your non-negotiables, like one of them for me is

00:40:16.159 --> 00:40:28.080
culture. But within that, I think just having a sense of prioritization is really useful. So thanks,

00:40:28.080 --> 00:40:40.320
Joe. I think a really good piece of advice is it's easy to think you need to build a lot of

00:40:40.320 --> 00:40:45.919
new skills in order to make a transition. And I don't think that's true. I think you should focus

00:40:45.919 --> 00:40:52.639
on polishing your existing skills rather than building new ones. Once you're in the job,

00:40:52.639 --> 00:40:56.560
then you can build new ones. But just you have a lot more skills than you realize.

00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:01.360
And if you just polish those and then like refine them, you know, if you're doing multiple

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:06.320
regression in your work, great. But I want you to know multiple regression like all the way down to

00:41:06.320 --> 00:41:10.080
the foundations before, you know, you don't need to start learning like every machine learning

00:41:10.080 --> 00:41:16.399
technique in the book. You know, you can get a first job just on multiple regression, but know

00:41:16.399 --> 00:41:24.479
it really well. And just tied to that, though, is that doesn't mean that the job you're qualified

