Sure. I've had, I have a lot of academic training, and I've never been much of an academic

00:44:55.360 --> 00:45:01.040
person. I feel very pragmatically driven. It was like 20% of the work was getting new results,

00:45:01.040 --> 00:45:07.040
but 80% was always saying how wrong they might be, and reporting on the different ways to do

00:45:07.199 --> 00:45:12.399
things that might end up wrong or where your data came from, and I never enjoyed that part of it.

00:45:13.760 --> 00:45:20.639
But the people that I've worked with, the more academic they are, and one of the people I work

00:45:20.639 --> 00:45:26.959
closest with right now is an MD PhD, and it never feels like some of the tasks that we work on

00:45:26.959 --> 00:45:35.040
together are done enough or correct enough or accurate enough, and it creates this

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:44.399
I can never really tell the people who depend on our deliverables how done he feels, or a former

00:45:45.360 --> 00:45:51.520
co-worker, we were fine-tuning financial marketing models together, and he would say,

00:45:51.520 --> 00:45:56.879
but this is wrong. This is not the way to do it, and I would constantly have to say,

00:45:58.399 --> 00:46:01.840
does the data validate that there is lift or that we're getting

00:46:01.919 --> 00:46:10.800
incremental lift or that the modeling is actually producing gains? Would it work if you put this in,

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:15.199
does the data show that this might work? And he would say, yes, but this is not the right way to

00:46:15.199 --> 00:46:22.800
do it. So it was this, I felt like when working with a lot of academics, they wanted so much more

00:46:23.120 --> 00:46:34.000
They wanted so much more completeness and accuracy and certainty about their approach to be

00:46:34.879 --> 00:46:41.120
validated by research, validated by other people who know the exact way to do

00:46:41.120 --> 00:46:46.000
small statistics, large statistics. I mean, I think one of the funniest things, you guys

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:51.520
can riff on this as long as you want, but when you get into big data, every single thing you measure

00:46:51.520 --> 00:47:00.000
is statistically significant, every single one. So what do you do when every possible number

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:07.679
has error bars this tiny? And it's really hard to get people past that frame of mind

00:47:07.679 --> 00:47:14.639
from what my experience is with academics in business. I think that actually points out a good

00:47:14.639 --> 00:47:22.399
transition point of like, what are the standards you're working to? If you are doing basic

00:47:22.399 --> 00:47:28.479
research and you're trying to build knowledge, then having this exclusive body of

00:47:28.479 --> 00:47:36.239
rigorous findings is the goal. That's not the goal at most businesses. Again, if you're

00:47:36.239 --> 00:47:40.879
doing medical research, then that's different. You actually, there is more of a

00:47:40.879 --> 00:47:45.679
scientific goal in there. But oftentimes, you think of businesses or often it's more of

00:47:45.679 --> 00:47:51.679
an investment strategy. And so now it's not about building an exclusive body of knowledge, it's

00:47:51.679 --> 00:47:58.000
about really optimal stopping. How long should we explore for so that we can exploit that

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:05.520
knowledge for maximum gain? And that's a different standard. It's not a lower

00:48:05.520 --> 00:48:09.520
standard, it's a different goal. And then that goal brings with it a different standard. So

00:48:10.479 --> 00:48:17.679
that's a change of mindset that you should be prepared to make. It's not

00:48:17.679 --> 00:48:22.879
going to serve you well to bring over academic standards to an environment where those won't

00:48:22.879 --> 00:48:28.479
serve you. So yeah, most business settings are going to be more about optimization than they are about

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:33.919
building scientific knowledge, although there will be some overlap.

00:48:34.479 --> 00:48:38.800
But yeah, it's a different standard is my answer.

00:48:39.679 --> 00:48:44.560
Yeah, and Eugene, your question kind of reminds me of a conversation I had very early on when I

00:48:44.560 --> 00:48:51.040
first got into industry, which was that, you know, in academia, what we care about is,

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:57.360
if you get a result, like, let's say you run an experiment, and, you know, your null result is

00:48:57.360 --> 00:49:03.280
like nothing, or you're, you know, the kind of the worst case is basically nothing changes,

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:06.879
right? Like, that's like, in academia, that's like the worst case. Now you don't have anything that

00:49:06.879 --> 00:49:11.439
you can report on. But if you get an unexpected result, either way, it's more positive than you

00:49:11.439 --> 00:49:15.360
thought, or it's more negative than you thought. Now you have an interesting result. And you can

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:20.479
talk about it and try to figure out causality and all these things. In business, kind of to

00:49:20.479 --> 00:49:25.280
Joe's point, if academia is about building knowledge, in business, I say a lot of the

00:49:25.280 --> 00:49:30.320
times, it's just about reducing risk. So a lot of the time, the standard of decision making

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:36.479
is we don't want, actually, a good result would be like that nothing changes, or it's positive.

00:49:36.479 --> 00:49:41.760
And the bad result is if it makes the outcomes that we care about worse, right? And so that's,

00:49:41.760 --> 00:49:46.560
that, to me, is such a fundamental change in how you look at it. Because if you're trying to be

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:50.719
like, oh, should we roll out this change in our business? Really, what a lot of leaders care

00:49:50.719 --> 00:49:55.120
about is they just want to make sure that it doesn't make things worse, right? And so either

00:49:55.120 --> 00:50:00.959
if it's the same or better, then that's great. But that same result in academia, if it's the same,

00:50:00.959 --> 00:50:07.520
is seen as like a not very valuable result. And I think that that shift is quite fundamental.

00:50:07.520 --> 00:50:12.479
And it's understandable, I think that many people struggle with that shift, because,

00:50:12.479 --> 00:50:17.360
you know, you're in any organization with its own values set and things like that, you do absorb

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:22.000
that way of thinking. And sometimes it needs to be called out extremely explicitly to help

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:27.520
people understand how they were thinking before. Because before in academia, everybody thought this

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:31.919
way, there was no need to call it out at all. You know, and so sometimes it's hard to identify when

00:50:31.919 --> 00:50:37.679
you're actually in a different kind of cultural environment. I know this time goes by so quickly.

